{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937110201/0058.xml":{"full_text":"It Seems to Me\nBy Heywood\nBROUN\nI\nWANT to address a few mild re\nmarks to those who say that ev\nery worker has a right to a job, and\nthat no outside agency whether that\nof capital or labor shall ever be al\nlowed to stop him in his God-given\nprivilege. This was pretty much the\nphilosophy of rugged individualism\nvoiced by Tom Girdler before the\npo\u2014===== Senate Post Of\nfice\ny aice Committee.\nBut under ques\n6\nF tioning by Sen.\nGreen of Rhode\nIsland, G i r d ler\ntook a good deal\nof it back.\nHe\nhh professed to be\nBh puzzled when the\nSenator\nwanted\nto know whether\nunemployed men\nfor whom there\nBroun was no opening\nalso possessed\na God-given right to a job. Under\ncross-examination Mr. Girdler ad\nmitted that he did not think the\nGovernment should undertake the\nresponsibility of furnishing jobs to\nthe jobless. So there in the philos\nophy of rugged individualism we\nmay note exception number one in\nthe right to work.\nH\nENRY FORD is another indus\ntrialist who is quite articulate\nin talking about the right of the in\ndividual to have a free choice as to\nwhether to work or not. But part\nof the system of Ford and other\nlarge companies is based upon sea\nsonal layoffs, and even the com\nplete shutting down of a plant when\nit is not economical to keep it open.\nAnd what does the employe do with\nhis right to work when he comes to\nthe plant and finds the gates are\nlocked? Can he put that right in\nhis pipe and smoke it or broil it to\nkeep his family from hunger?\nSome will say that he can go else\nwhere and take another job until\ntimes improve. But that may be a\nvery long walk, a walk right to the\nedge of the world and over.\nThe\nmechanical cotton picker is now\nonly a few steps away from being\npractical. When it is put into use,\nmore than a million men will be\nthrown out of employment. and all\nthat will remain with them will be\nthe God-given right to work. God\nundoubtedlj\u2019 did establish such a\nprinciple, but the machine age has\nsnatched it away.\nIS THAT fair? I\u2019ll do my own an\nswering and say, \"No!\u201d And it is\neven more unfair when the worker\nwho has not lifted a finger to bet\nter the conditions in his shop re\nceives all the gains, while the union\nmen who forced the benefits are\nthrown out on their ear.\nI might instance a present case\nconcerning a chain of stores in New\nYork.\nSome four hundred out of\nseven hundred employes organized\na union and entered into collective\nbargaining with the employer, the\nemployer agreed to a wage increase,\na year\u2019s contract and two weeks\u2019 va\ncation with pay, but he would not\ngrant the union shop, and so a\nstrike was called. Thereupon the\ncompany telegraphed to all its em\nployes that in spite of the strike the\nwage increase and the two weeks'\nvacation would be granted to all\nloyal workers who remained on the\njob.' Accordingly, 300 men get ben\nefits for which they did not, work.\nIndeed, they worked against them by\nrefusing to be represented in the\nbargaining. I do not think it can\nfairly be said that those who are\nwilling to reap where they have not\nsown are truly rugged and heroic\nThere must be some\nindividuals.\nmore appropriate name\u2014parasites\nwill do for a start.\nFinds Lack of Logic\nin Arguments Over\nComfort of Dogs\nEditor, The News:\nHAVE been reading the lashing\nback and forward on the topic of\nI\nthe dog with much interest. Altho\nI like a dog as a pet, I would think\nno more of him than a pet chicken,\ncat, bird or rabbit; I don\u2019t think he\nis worth all the hard feelings caused\nin his defense.\nIt is rather a hard pill to swallow\nfor a mother to see the considera\ntion a dog gets from some people\nto whom children are only \u201cbrats.\"\nIn this day, when little children\nare in want of food and a decent\nplace to live, we call ourselves good\ncitizens by arguments that a dog\nis not treated fair.\n\u201cA HUMAN MOTHER.\u2019.\u2019.\nSIDE GLANCES\nby George Clark\nr\ndi i nr\nASBaRetaP\ni\ni\nf.\nan tn NenGtvS w.iuiiMy\n\n1-2\n\u201cI can\u2019t remember whether or not I told my husband to\nmeet us here, and if I did he probably has forgotten it.\u201d\nWagner's Backing of Mahoney\nIs Decried by Rabbi Israel\nBy RABBI DAVID L. ISRAEL\nI think that Sen. Robert F. Wag\nner is one of the finest men in\nAlso, from\nAmerican political life.\neverything I have heard, Judge Ma\nhoney, now running against La\nGuardia for may\nor of New York\nCity, is an at\ntractive and hon\nest person.\nAs an out-of\ntowner, I might\nperhaps be ex\npected not to be\nconcerned with\nthe present New\nYork mayorality\nIsrael\ncampaign.\nBut\nthat campaign\nhas\nsignifi\na\ncance for every\nAmerican, even to the smallest ham\nlet. At a time when other nations\nen masse have lost their faith in\ndemocracy\u2014at a time when democ\nracy is under the most vicious sort\nof attacks\u2014this Mahoney-LaGuardia\ntussle has a nation-wide significance\nfar beyond its immediate implica\ntions.\nSen. Wagner has come out for\nMahoney. Mahoney is not only a\nfellow Democrat but his life-long\nfriend. But Sen. Wagner knows full\nwell that LaGuardia has, despite\nsome inevitable mistakes, been one\nof the best mayors New' York City\nhas ever had.\nYet Sen. Wagner, a sort of po\nlitical hero to me and millions of\nothers, not only supports his boy\nhood chum against a man who has\nmade a brilliant record, but he\nsupports the Democratic opponent of\nThomas Dewey. Even we non-New\nYorkers know Dewey as the one\nman in many years who has coped\nsuccessfully with New York gang\nland. In other words, Bob Wagner\nhas become, for the moment at\nleast, a Democratic party hack.\nI don\u2019t. believe that the Wagner\nendorsement is going to help Ma\nhoney and Hastings to the extent\nthat their forces imagine. I do feel,\nhowever, to my intense sorrow, that\nit is going to dim the luster of\none of the real luminaries in our\npolitical firmament. It will react on\nWagner himself.\nSen. Wagner must surely admit\nthat despite Mahoney\u2019s honesty and\naffability, LaGuardia represents, to\nan exceptional degree, the same so\ncial philosophy as does Wagner\nhimself. The Senator surely recog\nnizes the fact that the labor forces\nsupporting LaGuardia are much\nmore of the Wagner type than those\nwho have come out for Mahoney.\nBob Wagner must absolutely realize\n\u2014keen person that he is\u2014that while\nMahoney is not Tammany\u2019s first\nchoice, he now has Tammany sup\nport, and that the only truly ef\nfective way to crush Tammany as\nnever before is to re-elect La\nGuardia.\nOf Sen. Wagner's espousal of\nHastings as against Dewey, the less\nsaid the better. It represents a new\n\u201clow\u201d in blind party following by a\ngreat man who has been supposed\nto represent exactly the opposite in\nAmerican life.\nOf course, back of it all is the\nplan for Farley control of New York\npolitics. It is strongly rumored that\nJim Farley wants to be the next\ngovernor of New York and that a\nMahoney victory is vital to that am\nbition.\nEvery great career is entitled to\na few lapses from the heights. The\nbrilliant record of Sen. Robert F.\nWagner can perhaps lead us to for\ngive what he is now doing, diffi\ncult as we find it to understand.\nBut it ought not to blind our\neyes to the fact that if democracy\nis not to receive another jolt, an\nintelligent and grateful electorate\nmust record its appreciation of faith\nful service by electing LaGuardia\nand Dewey. The rest of the nation\nanxiously awaits the momentous de\ncision.\nPalmisano Is Urged\nto Study Cost of\nLiving in D. C.\nEditor, The News:\n0\nUR new House D. C. Committee\nChairman, Rep. Palmisano of\nBaltimore, likes to compare Wash\nington with Baltimore. He promised\nan investigation of the costs of the\nmunicipal governments. He forgets\nthat Washington is the most ex\npensive city in the country in which\nto live (according to reports issued\nby the Bureau of Labor Statistics)\nwhereas Baltimore is one of the\ncheapest. Washington does not have\na large factory-worker population.\nRents and food are much higher in\nWashington.\nIf Palmisano can lower the cost\nof living in Washington, then he\ncould proceed to seriously consider\nlowering the costs of government.\nV. WITZEL.\nOSGOOD\u2019S IN LOVE! OSGOOD\u2019S\nIN LOVE!\nEditor, The News:\nTHE \"whinings\" of the sad young\nman from Boston are far prefer\nable to the semi-whimsical pontifi\neating of Osgood.\nMoreover there\nis a glaring fallacy in Osgood's\nthree-quarter column rambling\u2014he\nadvises the Bostonian to return to\nthat Elysium and yet, despite his\nown deep convictions, Osgood him\nself remains to be annoyed by our\nvanity and pin-headedness. Could\nit be that he has succumbed to the\ncharms of a flashing-eyed beauty\nfrom the District?\nobvious fraud.\nOsgood is an\nDELICATE SOUTHERN FLOWER,\nBAD HUMOR\nBy DAN KIDNEY\nDon't throw away your ear-muffs!\nGerald Smith has taken over Father\nCoughlin's radio contract.\nBelt-tightening thought for 1938:\nUncle Sam was a good fellow when\nhe had it!\nBusiness Recession\nEnd Not in Sight,\nU. S. Bureau Reports\nBy MARSHALL McNEIL\nThe present business recession may run well into 1938,\nthe U. S. Bureau of Agricultural Economics reported\ntoday.\nBut this setback, the report indicated, may be merely\none of those that characterize a general upswing of the\nbusiness cycle.\nThe bureau pointed out that \"many\nof the conditions which in the past\nhave been associated with the ter\nmination of a major cyclical upswing\nin business activity now are absent.\"\nThe report, the most comprehensive\nissued by a Government agency since\nthe downswing started, is the basis\nfor a prediction by the bureau that\nthe prospect is for a less favorable\ndemand for farm products in 1938.\nMORE PRICE INCREASES\nThe bureau also said that retail\nprices probably have not yet reflected\nall the rise in wholesale prices ot\nmanufactured products and in mar\nketing costs. It said indications point\nto some further increases in retail\nprices of furniture, furnishings, shoes\nand fuel, but that the effect on living\ncosts of these increases probably will\nbe offset in part by lower prices for\nrayon and cotton clothing, meats and\nother foods. It believes that the rise\nin rents may continue, but at a\nslower rate than this year.\n\"The general upswing of a business\ncycle,\u201d\nthe bureau's\nreport\nsaid.\n\"usually is characterized by relatively\nshort recessions.\nBusiness sentiment\nbecomes\nless\noptimistic.\nsecurity\nprice decline, and businessmen post\npone extensive commitments for ex\npansion or rehabilitation.\n\"These conditions in turn lead to\nhesitant buying by potential consum\ners of many products. Stocks of fin\nished and semi-finished merchandise\nmay accumulate in dealers\u2019 hands and\norders received by manufacturers de\ncline as buying is placed on a hand\nto-mouth basis.\n\"Business appears to have entered\nsuch a phase in the latter part of\n1937, following the period of decided\noptimism in the winter of 1936-37.\nIt is difficult to determine how long\nsuch a recession will continue, but the\nappraisal of general conditions gives\nsome support to the impression based\non the situation for individual indus\ntries that it will run well into 1938.\u201d\nTEXTILES FACE SLUMP\nOf individual industries, the report\nsaid:\nTextiles\u2014Many textile mills were\noperating during the summer of 1937\nPlain Economics\nby John T. Flynn\nThe cocksureness of the New Deal here in Washington\nonly a year ago as it was riding to the great victory at\nthe polls in November seems to have filtered out of the\nCapitol. An air of perplexity and, in places, of gloom, has\nsucceeded it.\nThe fact is that the business recession and the stock mar\nket crash have hit the Administration a broadside blow. And\nthe first result has been to accentuate the division of coun\nsel among the various commissions and groups which ad\nminister the New Deal.\nThe\nwhole disturbance\ncenters\naround the bewilderment respecting\nthe widely advertised and obviously\nflat capital markets. For six months\nit has been apparent that capital was\nnot moving into business,\nthe summer de\nparted there was\na general realiza\ntion by business\nand by Washing\nton that there\ntrouble in\nwas\nthe wind.\nBusiness or\nrather the high\nly organized and\nvocal part of it\nwhich centers in\nAnd as\nFlynn\nhas\nW a 11-st\nbeen making use\nof the crisis to\ndrive thru Us pet projects. And it\nhas been making notable advances.\nThose pet projects are (1) reduc\ntion of stock margin.'- 12) relaxation\nof the curbs on the trading of cor\nporation executives; (3) repeal of the\ncapital-gains tax; 14, repeal of the\ncorporation undistributed-s u r p l u s\ntax; \u00bb5) a halt on the extension of\nTV A projects, and (6) a milder pol\nicy with reference to the Utility\nHolding Company Act.\nBalancing the budget might tie\nincluded in this; but as a matter\nof fact business, particularly Wall-st,\nis getting jittery about balancing\nthe budget, realizing that this, with\nout a corresponding rise in private\ncredit, will mean deflation and a\npossible general collapse.\nlargely on advance orders received\nthe preceding spring, and by the lat\nter part of the year unfilled orders\nhad been greatly reduced and there\nwere\nindications that considerable\nstocks of both cotton and woolen\ngoods had accumulated in the trade.\nThe lower cotton prices now prevail\ning will tend to offset part of these\nunfavorable conditions. Nevertheless,\na considerable decrease in the output\nof textiles in 1938 as compared with\n1937 is expected.\nIron and Steel\u2014An examination of\nthe prospects for demand from sev\neral industries using steel indicates\nthat production in 1938 will be less\nthan in 1937.\nAutos\u2014Some slackening in the rate\nof auto production in 1938 as com\npared with 1937 may occur. The re\nported relatively minor nature of the\nchanges in models for 1938, the\nhigher prices to be asked, the ex\nperted\nfor\nstringent terms\nmore\nfinancing purchases of both new and\nsecond-hand cars and the change in\ndirection of stock prices and incomes,\nmay result in a smaller replacement\ndemand for autos in 1938 than in\n1937.\nRAILS WITHOUT ORDERS\nRailroads\u2014The railroads are\nlikely to postpone as far as possible\ntheir orders for new equipment.\nConstruction\u2014The value of total\nbuilding during the first eight months\nof 1937 exceeded the same period in\n1936 by about 15 per cent, but after\nallowing for higher costs, the increase\nin volume of construction apparently\nwas only about 8 per cent. During\nthe past year building costs increased\nfrom 10 to 15 per cent, with an even\ngreater increase for residential types\nThis retarded the\nof construction.\ndevelopment of this industry in 1937.\nSome decrease in cost during 1938\nis possible and an increase in rents\nAn expected boom in\nmay occur.\nbuilding activity had been counted\nupon by many observers to more\nthan offset any slackening of the\nGovernment\u2019s support to business, but\npresent conditions in the building in\ndustry do not indicate any large ex\npansion in 1938.\nThere is a powerful group of ad\nvisers close to the President who\nfavor granting most if not all of\nthese requests.\nOf course, there are the earnest\nNew Dealers who stoutly resist any\nconcessions, but they seem to be\nvery much on the outside of the\nPresident's counsels.\nAlready the big concession on\nmargins has been made.\nThis was\ndone with great secrecy so as to\nprevent any of the liberal groups\nnear the President from even hear\ning about it until it was too late.\nNow reports are that the capital\ngains tax and the corporation sur\nplus tax are to be greatly modified\nAt the same time the most power\nful pressure is being brought to\nbear to permit insiders to trade in\ntheir own stocks. The conservatives\nsee that the President is in a fright\nened mood and is in a state of\nmind for concessions, and they ate\npressing the advantage.\nAmong conservative elements a\nlarge and influential section believe\nthat the business turn has com\npletely changed the whole situation\nand put into their hands a golden\nopportunity to get the President's\near and his good will.\nFrom all\nthis it is now perfectly clear that\nthe struggle to the death within\nthe\nAdministration\nbetween\nthe\nstanch New Dealers and the prag\nmatic politicians and busiiess men\nhas definitely begun.\nCopytiht, 1937","height":"21068","width":"14484"}}
